column1: Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities?
column6: ['Security and Conflict', 'Non-US Politics']
Not likely.

Assuming between 4 October and 31 December does not include potential New Year's Eve violence, I think the potential fatalities has all but diminished. It is possible the Chinese approach was to let the protests run their course and it appears to be working. Also, the infiltration of a criminal element into the protests will likely diminish support for the wider movement. I am honestly surprised, though grateful it wasn't worse.

Violence remains, however, HK police have managed to contain it without losing wider control. As the clock winds down on this question, I don't see any significant milestone/event that will spark violence that could lead to fatalities. My forecast is down significantly from earlier in the fall and reflects perhaps overall protest fatigue.
There is likely to be a big protest on 1st January, unlikely to be a further death before then.
Christmas and new year might be a heated time.

As far as I know there seem to have been two so far in that period, one of them only related to the protest (an accident). With only 10 days of a three months time span to go, three or more seems very unlikely to me.
https://time.com/5753585/hong-kong-worst-protest-over/
A bit of lost momentum due to legitimate policing:
lowering possibility of fatalities as it approaches the end of the month.
only 16 days left.

The violence seems to be abating. The Polytechnique University's issue seems to be clearing up, tho some bombs were disarmed at a high school this week. The question I have is are the HK people becoming tired protest fatigue.
I think it happened but it may be years before the story comes out.
-15%. Tensions seem less
Key drivers of protests, and therefore death-causing events, are subsiding on the time horizon of the question.
Decreasing forecast as tensions have seemed to reside.

Reducing forecast due to changes in local environment. Schools are out or close to release for holidays. There will have to be a significant trigger to boil things over again. This does not include targeted attempts by China and Hong Kong (Chinese Loyalist) to "Enhance" the level of confrontation which may in turn cause fatalities.
Hattip to @Chrisp for convincing me to throw caution to the wind. Lets hope the real caution is with the students and the officiers in HK.

Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities? No news is good news. Lets hope it stays that way.

The election seems to have calmed the situation for the moment, it broke the escalating cycle of violence we were seeing. I don't think we will see a return to the violent situations we were seeing in the next few weeks.
I continue to be surprised by resilience of protestors and restraint of Beijing. Lowering but always chance of accident or individual going too far...

Using an optimistic Copernican Principle, there have been no deaths since 14 November (28 days), therefore we can expect there to be none for the next 28 days. Therefore I should drop my prediction once again to close to zero. However, it's an overly simplified and wildly inaccurate way of forecasting that takes nothing into account other than the the most recent history. I'll reduce my prediction once again, this time by half. (Still higher than my original prediction)
Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities? Hundreds of thousands peacefully on the streets to show support.

Despite their levels of violent protest, the HK police have remained remarkably disciplined, but I'm not sure how long it will last.

Crowds lead to unpredictable behavior. If there is a stampede in close quarters, three or more could be trampled very quickly like has happened in soccer matches, the Hajj, and elsewhere. It is easy to miscalculate how a crowd reacts or how infrastructure cam magnify miscalculation.
I've been all over the map on this one, can't settle my mind.

The results of the election my quell unrest, but Carrie Lam continues to lack credibility. Her post election statement seems to offer an olive branch, but what will Beijing do with this development? They don’t back down and they don’t reconcile differences very well. After a short peaceful period I expect the violence will return.

Pulling down slightly: - university protests that dominated headlines have ended without a fatality - pro-democracy candidates won big in district elections. This demonstration of will could give pause to more violence which disenfranchises those who aren’t participating

Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities? Hoping that elections go smoothly with no fatalities.

I'm disheartened by the increase in violence by the protesters. The question is no longer the same as when this challenge started, it is now "will there be two or more deaths by Dec 31" I feel that is possible because of the escalation of violence by the protestors.

HK police are banning protesters from wearing masks in the run up to the 11/24 elections. No pressure release actions on either side (protesters vs. authorities). It is also worth considering the impact on tensions of external drivers, such as the US and the HK human rights bill that, if signed by President Trump, will enact sanctions and other actions unwelcome to the Chinese government. I think passage of the bill will accretes to "Yes" for the forecast of this question. No change in my forecast - BTW

Violence is escalating and there has already been one death.
Increasing violent police actions, Hong Kong protestors arming themselves with homemade weapons and Chinese military presence to "clean the streets" is the perfect formula for fatalities.

The HK Police are losing their authority through strong-arm tactics that are only antagonizing the citizens. This will increase protests and further erode governmental control over the police. They have been doing a remarkable job keeping casualties low, but as exhaustion sets in they will not be able to maintain their discipline.

It is just a matter of time before the Communist Party decides it has had enough. Granted, the financial and capital aspects that Hong Kong brings to the Chinese table are significant, but the bottom line is that the Party comes first. They need time to move the financial mechanisms and then they will step in and end the protests. We are seeing a ever increasing mainland military presence in Hong Kong now and it's just a matter of time.
Chinese government will try to descalate the conflict, to get back to the baby steps approach in limiting HK independence.

Shot protester sounds like they are recovering but elderly man hit by protesters brick has died. Up to two now. Little likelihood of no more deaths by the end of the year as the situation is only getting worse.

From Economist (note second last sentence): “Many speculate that the government will use the violence to justify imposing a curfew or cancelling district elections set for November 24th, even though Mrs Lam still says she wants the polls to go ahead. Pro-establishment candidates normally perform well at the district level, but this time pro-democracy politicians are expected to make considerable gains. That could unnerve Mrs Lam and the leadership in Beijing, since control of the 18 district councils could give the pro-democracy camp a bigger voice in Hong Kong’s legislature (six out of its 70 seats are reserved for councillors) and in the committee that chooses the chief executive (councillors make up nearly one-tenth of its 1,200 members). On November 12th the People’s Daily, the Communist Party’s main mouthpiece, said that holding “fair elections” would require “decisively” ending the riots. That seems a distant goal.”

It is sad that an 70-year old man died after being hit with brick amid Hong Kong protests. This death is the second fatality in the time frame of this forecast question. (The first one was a student that died from falling off a garage).

Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities? I am increasing my probabilty due to increased sphere of violence.

District Council elections are scheduled for November 24. The outcome of the elections are material to both the pro-establishment and pro-democracy camps. Cancelling or postponing the elections will increase tension on the anti-establishment side, as they will accuse the current government leadership of doing so to maintain a grip on power. Holding the elections poses risks to the establishment of a diminished voice if their candidates lose seats. Thus, the HK security forces have reason to ramp of efforts to maintain order and quell protests in the run up. Increasing my forecast by 5%.

Two serious events - One person fell and died, another shot in the chest. One probably accidental death. One self defense because of escalating protester violence. I'm increasing my forecast because death has become more probable.
Escalation and more escalation, both from the protesters and the response. I hope I am wrong but I feel the chances are not relatively high of further fatalities.

There have been 4 critical injuries in the protests, including 1 death. These have all occurred over the past 2 weeks for a rate of 2 critical injuries per week. At the current ratio, we’d need 8 more critical injuries in the next 6 weeks. This math would put the odds at about 75%.

1 already dead, another protester in critical condition after being shot and now an elderly man is in a sorry state after being hit by a brick. Felt like I should have upped the chance a while back. Nothing looks hopeful there now.

This is now quite likely as the HK Police enhance their response and tactics to restore the rule of law on the streets. Routinely policing appearing to have given way to a more robust type of public order control.

I live in Hong Kong. I can't go to the office this week due to sporadic violence. So far today, we've had: Photos of protestors carrying gas bottles to use a bombs, rumors of students stealing chemicals in their universities to make weapons, videos of other angry citizens fighting back and trying to stone some protestors. It clearly has to get worse before it gets better, so I am upping my percentage. On the other hand, HKers are very controlled, violence in HK is generally more psychological than physical - that's why my initial forecast was so low. However I think we have now crossed the Rubicon and significant amounts of blood will be spilt. For today's happenings, see: https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3037453/hong-kong-protests-city-braces-third-straight-day-travel

Protests are intensifying. There are protests on weekdays now instead of just on weekends. Protest - police confrontations have spread to the Chinese University of Hong Kong. The combing force of students from an elite university with high school students and the populous indicates that the protests are not going to die down soon. At the same time, the government is taking increasing stronger stands to the the protests, with urging from the Chinese government. There is increasing chance of fatality.

I had dipped down to 60% recently, but have decided to calibrate a bit based on increasing tensional forces. Like tectonic plates, the result with be faulting (more violence and damage), rather than bending or stretching plastically (i.e. compromise or peaceful resolution).

Between 4 October 2019 and 31 December 2019, will anti-government protests in Hong Kong result in three or more fatalities? Protests started on March 31st (7 months ago) and the first death occurred on Monday. That would suggest a 14% probability of a death in any 7 month period. Assuming independence (we’ll get back to this in a second) that would be a 7% probability of 2 more deaths in a 7 month period. But there are only 2 months until this question expires, so the answer would have to fall to 2-3%.

Unfortunately, first death . Police said they were investigating the case and denied allegations they had obstructed medical assistance or that officers had pushed Chow. A spokesperson for the Hong Kong government expressed “great sorrow and regret”.
I think it's quite unlikely, however 3 is a relatively small number, and just one unfortunate event could cross that threshold. Tension is still high, so that's how I've come to 20%.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-protests/hong-kong-extradition-bill-officially-killed-but-move-unlikely-to-end-unrest-idUSKBN1X20OF The bill has been pulled, which has become only part of the point of the protests but will give a good reason for hanging it up for those who are tired or scared or otherwise uninterested. Smaller and calmer crowds usually suffer fewer chances of fatalities--especially where police agencies are, shall we say, relatively well trained and tightly supervised.

Reaffirming my forecast. Yes, the base rate is low for deaths in protests in HK (Inside View), However, an Outside View would take into account at least similar protests in similar circumstances. I am not sure what the base rate is, but it is assuredly higher. In any case, tension continue rise. Consider:

Even amidst escalating violence, there is massive incentive from both the authorities and the protesters to preserve life. Will someone get hurt? YES Will someone die as a direct result of the protest? Unlikely.

By accident I mean the voilence was committed without the intent to kill but it gets out of hand (e.g. death resulted from a severely burnt person). This holds unless China sends in troups, which is unlikely at this point.

There are very few guns in circulation in Hong Kong, so the risks of a shoot out remain low. Nevertheless, the remaining protestors are more violent (setting Chinese owned shops on fire this weekend) so the possibility of an accident remain.

The base rate implies that the probability of fatalities occurring is extremely low. There appears to have been 0 deaths resulting from anti-government protests since the 1997 handover of HK from Britain to China, as @KitsonJ has pointed out. However, as many others have noted, there is good reason to give little weight to this base rate given how enormous this protest movement is and how great of a threat it is perceived to be by Beijing, especially relative to past protest movements in HK. So instead, I will mostly consider the base rate to be the fatalities/near-fatalities thus far in this current protest movement.

I'm actually using this questions with my AP Stats students to have them practice forecasting. There's only five students plus me, but this was our aggregate forecast after using the history of protests as a starting point to come up with subjective probability estimates of witnessing a fatality, and then taking into account the 80 day time frame left and the fact that we need to witness at least 3 deaths.
even it happen, gov will cover it. unless real time issue. if real time issue, it would not happen more than three. so i believe it will keep really low %
81 days left.

Normally, I hate making 50/50 forecasts. However, in that case I feel the situation is that balanced. I do not believe the government or police want to use lethal force to stop the demonstrations but, given how high tensions are, a small miscalculation by any one of a number of angry people could quickly escalate into shootings.

I am making this forecast because given the political climate of China at the moment; seeing the pressure from the US in regards to trade, the Uighur "genocide," moves in the Middle East and the Horn of Africa, China will want to seem like a morally positive state to support. With the Hong Kong protestors being so against rejoining mainland China, this damages their international image, so they will want to subdue protests as fast and quietly as possible.
While Hong Kong erupts into chaos, it's unlikely that it'll result in death, unless completely accidental.
To forecast this question, one needs to understand the history of Hong Kong and its protest movements.

HK is being very careful to impose laws that allow for incarceration without resorting to violence [1] and the threat of China coming in to enforce peace is very likely, given that the protestors are fighting harder now that the HK administration is coming down harder on them [2]. The current law keeps China out, but they can send troops as needed [3], though I wonder who would enforce that law right now if China violated it. Britain has plenty of their own problems to manage, the US seems to be running away from democratic complainants either to avoid issues or as a favor to those in the position of power, and there doesn't seem to be much of a unified coalition to oppose China moving in to preserve security and economic/social stability except through sanctions and diplomatic measures. Although China isn't in the strongest position now and they have been conservative about taking aggressive positions that they haven't prepared for well in advance and are generally well-prepared to handle, I think they would be more willing to move in before the protests lead to general chaos than to let them become a trigger or signal for something less manageable now or in the future. And China will want something that can be done behind the scenes or done without state violence, and do it quickly and efficiently. There have already been rumors and official clarifications of fatalities [4], and unless someone dies on the street in front of a camera, I wonder how clear the fatality outcome will be. I would expect a great many injuries, not many fatalities now that it's a real threat.
When the upcoming crack down comes there will be bloodshed.
